div.p:
That my Government had never believed any protocol or arrangement to be necessary
                    previous to the organization and exercise of its functions by the Tribunal
                    Arbitral;

That according to the constitution and laws of Ecuador, all conventions with
                    another Government, no matter by what name they may be designated, are subject
                    to the approval of Congress and to a long proceeding;

That it desires, consequently, that the Honorable Judge A. L. Miller, the Arbiter
                    named by President Wilson in conformity to the contract of June 14, 1897, may go
                    as soon as possible to exercise his office in Ecuador;

That now that the Arbiters are already named, they need do nothing except to
                    present themselves at Quito and take possession of their office before the
                    proper Ecuadorean judge;
